{\fs20 Views about the structure of memory have gone through many different phases throughout the history of the study of memory, which can be traced back to the early Greek philosophers. However, one \line characteristic of memory structure that is now commonly accepted is that a part of memory is oriented toward events that have just occurred, while a part is related to events in the past. This is not a new idea. In fact, in 1890, William James wrote of an \ldblquote elementary\rdblquote  or \ldblquote primary\rdblquote  memory that makes us aware of the }
{\fs20 \ldblquote just past.\rdblquote  He distinguished this from a \ldblquote secondary memory\rdblquote  that is for \ldblquote properly recollected objects.\rdblquote  To primary memory, James allocated items that are lost and never brought back into consciousness, whereas to secondary memory, he allocated ideas or data that are never lost. \u173 ?
Although they may be }{\fs20 \ldblquote absent from consciousness,\rdblquote  they are capable of being recalled.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The debate about the structure of memory has centered on how this distinction between memory for immediate things and memory for things in a more distant past fits into a structural arrangement. At present, the bulk of the evidence supports the view that there are two components of memory.}
{\*\cs55\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\super 1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  The evidence for this comes from two different but complementary research approaches to the study of human memory. One of these is taken from the study of cognitive psychology, where inferences about the structure and function of memory are based on observing the behavior of individuals in memory situations. The other approach is that of the neuropsychologist or neurophysiologist, who is interested in explaining the structure of memory in terms of what is occurring in the nervous system during behavioral changes related to memory. Research evidence from both of these approaches provides convincing evidence that the memory system comprises at least two components that are definable by their distinct functions. Also, it is important to note that after reviewing and evaluating the relevant \u173 ?
research literature, Healy and McNamara (1996) concluded that although some elaboration of various aspects of the component model of memory \u173 ?
is\u8239 ?needed, the model remains a useful means of \u173 ?understanding human memory.\par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 A Two-Component Memory Model\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Several different models of human memory have been developed to represent its component structure. One of the most enduring and influential was \u173 ?
presented by Atkinson and Shiffrin in 1968. Using a computer analogy, they conjectured that mem\u173 ?ory structure should be thought of as similar to com\u173 ?
puter hardware. They considered that the software that \u173 ?allows the computer to function constitutes \u173 ?the}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3\u8239 ?
\ldblquote control processes,\rdblquote  which involve memory processes such as storage and retrieval of information and are under the control of the person. The structural components, they concluded, comprise a sensory register, }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 short-term store, and long-term store.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Since the time of Atkinson and Shiffrin\rquote s presentation of theory of memory structures, the primary theoretical problem has been to determine the exact nature of these structures. While debate continues about memory structure, there is general agreement that this structure of memory should include different memory storage components in addition to serving a functional role for what the person does with the information in each component. (To read a brief overview of the neuroscience debate about memory structure, see Nee, Berman, Moore, & Jonides, 2008.)}
{\fs20 \par An excellent example of a memory structure model that accommodates these characteristics was proposed by Baddeley (1986, 1995, 2003}
{\fs20 , 2012}{\fs20 ). According to this view, memory is seen as comprising two functional systems, }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
working memory}{\fs20  and }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 long-term memory}{\fs20  (see figure 10.1). Each memory system is defined in terms of its functions. Although a number of different functions have been proposed, we will focus primarily on three: putting information in memory (referred to as storage processes), getting information out of memory (referred to as retrieval processes), and specific functions in each component.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb390\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
