{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 The }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 working memory}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  should be thought of as a system that incorporates characteristics and }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 functions traditionally associated with sensory, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 perceptual, attentional, and short-term memory }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 processes. Working memory operates in all situations requiring the temporary use and storage of information and the \u173 ?
execution of memory and response production processes (see Baddeley, 1995). Baddeley (2003) stated that the working memory is a limited capacity system, which tempo}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 rarily maintains and stores information and provides }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \ldblquote an interface between perception, long-term memory, and action\rdblquote  (p. 829). As such, working memory includes memory functions traditionally \u173 ?
ascribed to }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 short-term memory,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  as well as other functions typically associated with the \u173 ?
attention-related }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 processes we discussed in chapter 9 (Engle, 2002).}{\*\cs55\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0\super
