{\fs20 Working Memory Functions\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Working memory is both a place where information is stored for a short time and a functionally \u173 ?active structure. These two characteristics of working memory enable people to respond according to the demands of a \ldblquote right now\rdblquote  situation. To do this, }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i working memory plays a critical role in decision making, problem solving, movement production and evaluation, and long-term memory function.}
{\fs20  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 With regard to influencing long-term memory function, working memory provides essential processing \u173 ?
activity needed for the adequate transfer of information into long-term memory. Finally, it is important to note that an important working memory function is to serve as an }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 interactive workspace}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  where various memory processing activities can occur, such as integrating the information in working memory with information that has been retrieved from the more permanent, long-term memory.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 According to Baddeley\rquote s conception of working }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
memory, its functions are related to three subsystems. The first two }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 subsystems store}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
 different types of \u173 ?information. One is the }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 phonological loop,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
 which is responsible for the short-term storage of verbal \u173 ?information. Second is the }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1
visuospatial sketchpad}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 , which stores}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  visually detected spatial information for short periods of time. The third subsystem, the }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 central executive,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  coordinates the information in working memory, which includes informa\u173 ?
tion retrieved from long-term memory. Neurologically, these components of working memory are localized in various brain regions, including the parietal cortex, Broca\rquote s area, premotor cortex, occipital cortex, and the frontal cortex (Baddeley, 2003).}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Researchers have also proposed that a fourth subsystem might exist in working memory, the }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
motor store}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  (e.g., Jaroslawska, Gathercole, & Holmes, 2018). It is not clear whether the proposed motor store is a separate subsystem in working memory or a component of the visuospatial sketchpad, perhaps encoding kinesthetic information. Evidence for the motor store comes from experiments showing a distinct advantage for the verbal recall of action sequences when participants perform the sequences during encoding or anticipate having to perform them during recall. This advantage is known as the }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 action advantage}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  (e.g., Waterman et al., 2017). For example, a sequence like }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \ldblquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 pick up the cup, point to the pencil, slide the ruler, and point to the paper}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  will be recalled more accurately verbally when participants perform the sequence in addition to either seeing it performed or hearing it described than when they only hear it or see it (Jaroslawska et al., 2018). Researchers are currently exploring how the proposed motor store might lead to a reconceptualization of Baddeley}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 s description of working memory.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Because working memory stores and processes information, it is important to consider each function \line separately. In terms of storing information, two characteristics of working memory are essential to understand: the length of time information will remain in working memory, which is called }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 duration,}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  and the amount of information that will reside in working memory at any one time, which is called }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 capacity.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Duration\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Our understanding of the duration of information in working memory comes from research that investigated short-term memory. Peterson and Peterson (1959) were the earliest to report \u173 ?
research related to the remembering of words presented one time each. They showed that we tend to lose information }{\fs20 \line }
{\fs20 (i.e., forget) from working memory after about only }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 20 to 30 sec. The first experiment published relating }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 working memory storage duration to motor skills was by Adams and Dijkstra in 1966. }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
Their}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  experiment indicated that arm positions in space that are experienced one time each are lost from working memory at a rate comparable to that of words.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The results of many other studies that followed }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 the Adams and Dijkstra investigation generally }{\fs20
supported the conclusion that the duration of movement information in working memory is about 20 to 30 sec. Information that is not processed further or rehearsed is lost.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb250\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Capacity\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 We are concerned with not only }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i how long}{\fs20  infor\u173 ?mation will remain in short-term storage, but also }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i how much}{\fs20  information we can accommodate. The issue of capacity in working memory was originally presented by George Miller in 1956, in an article that has become a classic in the memory literature. Miller provided evidence to indicate that we have the \u173 ?
capacity to hold about }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i seven items (plus or minus two items),}{\fs20  such as words or digits, in short-term storage. To increase the \ldblquote size\rdblquote  of an item in memory involves a control process termed }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i organization,}{\fs20  which we will consider later in this discussion. The newly created larger item, or \ldblquote chunk\rdblquote  as Miller called it, enables people to recall far more than five to nine individual items at a time. However, research has shown that although the size of a chunk may \u173 ?
increase, working memory\rquote s capacity for storing them remains constant at about seven (Cowan, Chen, & Rouder, 2004; Mathy & \u173 ?
Feldman, 2012). Thus in terms of storage capacity, items maintained in working memory can vary in size. One of the problems researchers have experienced in investigating the capacity limit of working memory is determining how to objectively define and measure an \ldblquote item\rdblquote  or chunk.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The definition and measurement problem has been especially problematic for researchers interested in motor skills who are interested in testing Miller\rquote s capacity hypothesis in terms of the remembering of movements. In spite of this problem, a few researchers }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 have reported investigations of the capacity limits of working memory for movements. In general, their results agree with the 7 }
{\*\cs57\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \'b1}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  2 range proposed by Miller. For example, in one of the first \u173 ?
investigations of this issue, Wilberg and Salmela (1973) reported that an eight-movement sequence of arm-positioning movements was the upper limit of working memory capacity for movements. In another study, Ille and Cadopi (1999) asked twelve- and thirteen-year-old female gymnasts to reproduce a sequence of discrete gymnastics movements after watching the sequence one time on a videotape. The gymnasts\rquote  recall performance demonstrated a six-movement capacity limit for the more-skilled gymnasts and a five-movement limit for the less-skilled gymnasts. The results for these young gymnasts are in line with those reported by Starkes, Deakin, Lindley, and Crisp (1987) for young skilled ballet dancers, who showed evidence that an eight-\line movement sequence was their capacity limit.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }{\fs20 To account for research evidence that has shown that highly skilled individuals (i.e., experts) seem to have a working memory capacity that is greater than that of the general population, Ericsson and Kintsch (1995) proposed a memory mechanism they called }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i long-term working memory.}{\fs20  In addition to having a larger working memory storage capacity, experts also show evidence that performing certain secondary tasks does not interfere with their performance of the activity at which they are skilled. Experts in an activity use long-term \u173 ?
work\u173 ?ing memory when they must have access to a large amount of relevant knowledge at their \u173 ?disposal to use while performing the activity. In\u8239 ?
addition, the experts use long-term working memory to integrate new information with previously \u173 ?acquired knowledge. It is important to note that as is commonly characteristic of expertise (which we will discuss more fully in chapter 12), long-term working memory is skill specific, which means that it develops as expertise in a skill rather than being a common component of working memory.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Processing Activities\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Information that is active in working memory is processed (or manipulated) in such a way that it can be used to achieve the goal of the problem at hand. The goal may be to remember what you have just been told or shown to do so that you can do the task. Or you may need to use this information to solve a specific movement problem. And in both cases, you would like to remember what you did in each performance situation so that you can use your experience as a reference to help you in some future performance situation. In each case, you will involve working memory processing activities to \u173 ?
enable you to achieve different goals.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Consider some examples of motor skill perfor\u173 ?mance situations in which these different working memory processing activities could occur. Suppose your golf instructor has just given you a specific \u173 ?
instruction to concentrate on your hand position as you swing a golf club. You must not only remember this instruction as you swing, but also retrieve from long-term memory the correct hand position and evaluate your present hand swing compared with the ideal. Of course, how successfully you make this comparison on your own depends on your stage of learning. But carrying out this verbal instruction invokes the working memory.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 Suppose you have just watched a dancer perform a sequence of dance movements and you must}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5
 }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 now perform that sequence. Working memory processing activity would be involved because you must keep in memory the visually presented sequence of movements and translate that visual information into motor performance. Involved in this translation process would be retrieving from long-term memory the movement information required to carry out the sequence.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Consider also the following example. You are a patient in an occupational therapy session and are given a complex puzzle to put together. You study the pieces and try to determine how the specific pieces fit together. You continually try to match pieces as in the completed puzzle. And you try to determine an appropriate movement strategy that would allow you to put the pieces together quickly and with little \u173 ?
error. Working memory would be \u173 ?actively involved in this problem-solving situation because you carried out several activities requiring several different perception, remembering, and \u173 ?
performance characteristics that must be done virtually simultaneously.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Long-Term Memory\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 The second component system in the memory }{\fs20 structure is }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 long-term memory}
{\fs20 ,}{\fs20  which is a more permanent storage repository of information. It is what we typically think of when the term }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i
memory}{\fs20  }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 is mentioned. William James (1890) considered }{\fs20 long-term memory as \ldblquote memory proper.\rdblquote  This is the component of memory that contains information about specific past events as well as our general knowledge about the world.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 In terms of the }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 duration}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  of information in long-term memory, it is generally accepted that the information resides in a relatively permanent state in long-term memory. Usually, \ldblquote forgotten\rdblquote  information that is stored in long-term memory is there, but the person is having difficulty locating it. Thus, measuring forgetting and remembering in long-term memory situations can be a tricky problem. We will come back to this important point later in this chapter.\par }
{\fs20 With regard to the }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i capacity}{\fs20  of long-term memory, it is generally agreed that there is a relatively unlimited capacity for information in long-term memory (e.g., Chase & Ericsson, 1982). In fact, we know neither how much information a person can store in memory nor how to measure the capacity of long-term memory. An unlimited capacity leads to unique problems, however. For example, organization of information in memory becomes much more critical in an unlimited capacity system than in one of a limited capacity. Thus, there is a need to understand how people organize the information stored in long-term memory. This and other related issues unique to long-term memory will be discussed throughout this chapter.\par }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 In terms of information duration and capacity }{\fs20 characteristics, it becomes obvious that long-term memory is distinct from working memory. Another distinct characteristic of long-term memory is the type of information that is stored there. In the following sections, three types of information stored in long-term memory will be discussed.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb140\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Procedural, Semantic, and Episodic Memory\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In a commonly referred-to model of long-term memory, Tulving (1985) proposed that there are at least three \ldblquote systems\rdblquote  in long-term memory: }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i proce\u173 ?dural, semantic,}{\fs20  and}{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i  }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i episodic}{\fs20  }{\fs20 memories. Each of these systems differs in terms of how information is acquired, what information is included, how information is represented, how knowledge is expressed, and the kind of conscious awareness that charac\u173 ?
terizes the operations of the system. We will briefly consider each of these systems and how they \u173 ?function and differ.\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb250\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-1\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Procedural memory.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
\u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 This memory system may have the most direct relevance to our discussion of long-term memory because it relates specifically to storing and retrieving information about motor skills. Procedural memory is best described as the memory system that enables us to know }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \ldblquote how to do\rdblquote  something, as opposed to enabling us to know \ldblquote what to do.\rdblquote  This distinction is readily seen in situations where you can perform a skill very well (i.e., \ldblquote how to do it\rdblquote ), but you are not able to verbally describe very well what you did (i.e., \ldblquote what to do}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \rdblquote ).\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The procedural memory system enables us to \u173 ?respond adaptively to our environment by carrying out learned procedures so that we can achieve specific action goals. For the performance of motor skills, procedural memory is critical because }
{\fs20 \line }{\fs20 motor skill is evaluated on the basis of producing an appropriate action, rather than simply verbalizing what to do. According to Tulving, an important characteristic of procedural memory is that procedural knowledge can be acquired only through \ldblquote overt behavioral responses,\rdblquote  which, for motor skills, means physical practice.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-4\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Semantic memory.\u8194\'20}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 According to Tulving (1985), semantic memory can be characterized by \ldblquote represent\u173 ?ing states of the world that are not perceptually present\rdblquote  (p. 387) to us right now. This means that we store in this memory system our }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 general knowledge}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  about the world that has developed from our many experiences. This includes specific factual knowledge, such as when Columbus reached America or the name of the tallest building in America, as well as conceptual knowledge, such as our concepts of \ldblquote dog\rdblquote  and \ldblquote love.\rdblquote  How information is represented in semantic }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 memory is currently the source of much debate. The debate ranges from suggestions that all experiences are represented in some fashion in memory to suggestions that individual experiences are not represented in semantic memory, but rather, only abstractions, such as prototypes or schemas, are represented.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-2\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Episodic memory.\u8194\'20}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 We store in episodic memory our knowledge about personally experienced events, along with their temporal associations, in \u173 ?
subjective }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 time. It is this memory system that enables us to \ldblquote men}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 tally }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \lquote travel back\rquote  in time\rdblquote  (Tulving, 1985, p. 387). }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Tulving views episodic memory as \ldblquote oriented to the past in a way in which no other kind of memory, or memory system, is\rdblquote  and as \ldblquote the only memory system that allows people to consciously reexperience past experiences}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote  (Tulving, 2002, p. 6). An example here would be your memory of an important life event. You are very likely to recall this event in terms of both time and space. For example, if you were asked, \ldblquote Do you remember }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 your first day of school}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ?\rdblquote  you would retrieve that information from episodic memory. Episodic memory is usually expressed in terms of remembering some experience, or episode. When a person recalls an experience from episodic memory, it is a personal recollection of the event. Tulving (2002) also described episodic memory as a memory system that deteriorates easily and is more vulnerable than other memory systems to neural dysfunction. For performing motor skills, episodic memory can be the source for information that prepares you for an upcoming performance or helps you determine what you are now doing wrong that at one time you did correctly.\par }
\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Distinguishing between Knowing }{\fs20 \line What to Do and Doing It\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 An important part of relating the three memory systems of long-term memory with the learning and performance of motor skills is the distinction \u173 ?
between knowing what to do and knowing }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 how to do it. Some learning theorists have argued that the information in the episodic and semantic memory systems should be considered }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 declarative knowledge}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  (e.g., Anderson, \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
1987). This knowledge is specified as what we are able to describe (i.e., declare) if we are asked to \u173 ?do\u8239 ?so. Thus, declarative knowledge is specific to knowing what to do}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  in a situation. This type of knowledge is distinct from }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 procedural knowledge,}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  which typically cannot be verbalized or is difficult }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
to verbalize. As described earlier, }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 procedural }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 knowledge}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  enables the person to actually perform a skill. This distinction is a useful one and will be \u173 ?
referred to in various parts of this chapter.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 One of the few experiments that has directly distinguished these two types of knowledge as they \u173 ?relate to motor skill performance provides an excellent example of the difference between declarative and procedural knowledge. McPherson and \line Thomas (1989) classified nine- to twelve-year-old boys as \ldblquote expert\rdblquote  or \ldblquote novice\rdblquote  tennis players based on length of playing experience and tournament play. Novices had only three to six months playing experience. The \ldblquote experts,}
{\fs20 \rdblquote  who had at least two years of experience and had played in junior tournaments, were in an elite group for their age. The players were interviewed after each point (something that the researchers had previously established did not disrupt the quality of performance). Players were asked to state what they had attempted to do on the previous point. When this information was later compared with what they had actually done (which was analyzed from a videotape recording), some interesting results were obtained. First, in terms of having an effective strategy or action goal, the experts knew what to do nearly all the time, whereas the novices generally never knew what to do. Second, although the experts were quite capable }
{\fs20 \line }{\fs20 of demonstrating that they knew what action goal to establish in a specific situation, they were not always able to accomplish it in their performance of the \u173 ?
action. This suggests that the appropriate goal was \u173 ?established but there were problems in the physical execution of the \u173 ?
intended action.\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 A different approach to demonstrating the distinction between declarative and procedural memory is to show that people with memory impairment due to amnesia can learn to perform a motor skill despite evidence of impaired declarative memory related to the task. An example of this type of experiment was reported by Cavaco, Anderson, Allen, Castro-Caldas, and Damasio (2004); chronic amnesic patients were compared to matching normal participants in learning to perform five tasks that were based on real-world experiences, such as weaving fabric, tracing geometric figures, and pouring water into cylinders. The results showed that the amnesic }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 patients improved performance on all five tasks during practice trials and maintained improved performance levels 24 hours and 2 weeks later. In fact, their performance levels were comparable to the normal control participants. However, when the amnesic patients were given declarative memory tests as part of the 24-hour retention test, they performed much worse than the normal participants and showed no explicit recall of characteristics of any of the five tasks they had practiced.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Remembering and Forgetting\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 A variety of reasons exist to explain forgetting. But before discussing some of those reasons, some terms need to be identified and defined. }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 Encoding}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  is the transformation of information to be remembered into a form that can be stored in memory. }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 Storage}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  refers to the process of placing information in long-term memory. }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 Rehearsal}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  is a process that enables the individual to transfer information from the working memory to long-term memory. }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 Retrieval}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  involves the search through long-term memory for information that must be accessed and used in order to perform the task at hand.\par }
\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Assessing Remembering \line and Forgetting}{\fs21 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Researchers generally determine what or how much has been remembered or forgotten by using one or both of two categories of memory tests.\par }
\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Explicit Memory Tests\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 When we ask people to remember something, we are asking them to consciously call something to mind. Tests of memory that do this same type of thing are known as }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i explicit}{\fs20  memory tests. These tests assess what a person can }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i consciously remember.}
{\fs20  \line Two types of explicit memory tests that have been popular in memory research are known as \u173 ?recall tests and recognition tests.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw7 A }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw7 recall test}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw7  requires a person to produce }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4
a \u173 ?required response with few, if any, available }{\fs20 cues or aids. This test asks the person to \ldblquote recall\rdblquote  information that has been presented. In the verbal domain, these tests typically take the form of essay }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 or fill-in-the-blank tests. For example, a recall }{\fs20 test could ask, \ldblquote Name the bones of the hand.\rdblquote  For motor skills, a recall test requires the person to perform an action on command, such as }
{\fs20 \ldblquote Perform the skill I just demonstrated to you\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Show me how you tie your shoe.\rdblquote }
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 A }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw3 recognition test}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 , on the other hand, pro}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 vides some cues or information on which to base a response. In this type of test, a person\rquote s task is to recognize the correct response by distinguishing it from several alternatives. In the verbal domain, multiple-choice or matching tests are examples of recognition tests. For example, you could be asked, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \ldblquote Which of these is a bone of the hand?\rdblquote  You are then given four alternative answers from which to choose, where only one is correct. To answer the question, you need only to recognize which is the correct alternative, or which are the incorrect alternatives. For motor skills, an example for a \line }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i movement recognition test}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  would involve having a person produce several different movements and then asking which of these is the one just demonstrated or most appropriate for a specific situation.\par In terms of learning and performing motor skills, we are often confronted with both recall and recognition \ldblquote tests,}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote  sometimes in the same situation. For example, if a person must climb a ladder, he or she must }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 recall}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  what to do and how it should be done in order to safely and effectively climb the rungs to the desired height. When the person then climbs the ladder, he or she must recognize that the movements performed are the same as those he or she recalled. In a sport context, when a baseball or softball batter must decide whether or not to swing at a pitch, he or she engages in a recognition test when determining if the ball is in the strike zone or not. Then, to produce the appropriate swing, the batter must recall what to do to carry out this action and then be able to recognize if the swing that has been initiated is appropriate for hitting the pitch where it is thrown.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 An important benefit of recall and recognition tests is that each provides different information about what has been remembered or forgotten. It is possible for a person to fail to produce a correct response on a recall test, but be able to produce that response when it is one among several alternatives in a recognition test. A value of the recognition \u173 ?
test,\u8239 ?then, is that it enables the researcher to determine \u173 ?if information is actually stored in memory, even though retrieval cues or aids are needed by the person in order to gain access to that information.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Implicit Memory Tests\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Many times people have information stored in memory, but it is stored in such a way that they have difficulty accessing that information so that they can respond correctly on explicit memory tests. \line This type of situation is especially relevant for procedural memory, which we discussed earlier as one of the long-term memory systems. For example, suppose you were asked to describe the grammatical rules of a sentence you had just said. Although you may not have been able to identify these rules, you confirmed your knowledge of them by the sentence you articulated. As a result, you demonstrated that you had knowledge about grammar rules stored in memory, but in a form that could not be brought to a conscious level so you could verbalize the rules.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 For motor skills, we can assess implicit memory by asking a person to verbally describe how to perform a skill and then asking him or her to perform it. As is often the case, especially with highly skilled people, the person can successfully perform a skill but cannot verbally describe what he or she did. For example, if you were asked to verbally describe how you tie your shoes without using your hands, you might not be able to do it, or you might experience some difficulty doing it. Does this mean you don}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rquote t know how to tie your shoes or that you have forgotten how to tie your shoes? No; in terms of our earlier distinction between procedural and declarative knowledge, it means that you do not have access to, or immediate access to, your declarative knowledge about tying shoes. How would you provide evidence that you know how to tie your shoes? You would physically demonstrate tying your shoes, which would indicate that you had the procedural knowledge necessary to perform this skill.\par }
{\fs20 On the other hand, it is possible to know what to do (i.e., have declarative knowledge), but not be able to actually do what you know you should do (i.e., have poor procedural knowledge). This phenomenon was demonstrated very nicely in another experiment by McPherson and Thomas (1989), which was related to the one discussed earlier. They also gave young male basketball players an explicit paper-and-pencil test and asked them to indicate what they would do in a given basketball game situation. This information indicated declarative knowledge about what to do. An implicit test was also administered by observing what the players actually did in a situation to determine if they had the procedural knowledge necessary to do what they \u173 ?
indicated should be done. The results showed that many of the players knew what to do in each situation, but couldn\rquote t actually do it in a game.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 The Causes of Forgetting\par }\pard\plain \s18\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang2057
{\fs20 Trace Decay\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 When forgetting occurs with the passing of time, the cause is generally termed }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
trace decay}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  in the memory literature. It should be noted that the term \ldblquote trace\rdblquote  is not commonly used in contemporary memory research literature. However, it can be thought of as synonymous with what is referred to in this discussion as the memory representation of an action.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 An important point about trace decay is that it can be effectively tested as a cause of forgetting only in working memory. However, for long-term memory, a major problem is the practical impossibility of maintaining a no-interference test situation. For example, if you try to recall how to hit a slice serve in tennis after several years of not having performed it, you will have some initial difficulty remembering how to do it. Although time is a factor, you undoubtedly experienced the potentially interfering influences of the many cognitive and motor activities you have performed since you last performed this type of serve. Hence, we observe the interaction of interference and time in the long-term memory situation. As a result, we know very little about the influence of time on forgetting \u173 ?
information stored in long-term memory.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 Although time undoubtedly influences forget}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ting of information stored in long-term memory, it is more likely that forgetting involves the misplacing of information or interference from other activity rather than its decay or deterioration. One reason for this is the relative permanence characteristic for \u173 ?
information stored in long-term memory. Thus, forgetting typically refers to a retrieval problem rather than to information no longer in memory.\par }
\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb236\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Proactive Interference\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Activity that occurs }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i prior to}{\fs20  the presentation of information that is to be remembered and negatively affects the remembering of that information is known as }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 proactive interference}{\fs20 .}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb120\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Proactive interference in working memory.\u8194\'20}
{\fs20 Relatively convincing research evidence suggests that }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 proactive interference is a reason for forgetting }
{\fs20 movement information held in working memory. One of the best examples of this was provided in an experiment by Stelmach (1969) many years ago. Participants moved to either zero, two, or four locations on an arm-positioning task }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i before}{\fs20  moving to the location to be recalled. Following a retention \u173 ?interval of 5, 15, or 50 sec, they moved in reverse order to their estimates of each of the locations they had moved to. Thus, the first location recalled was }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 the criterion location. Results showed proactive }{\fs20\u173 ?interference effects as four prior movements and a }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 retention interval of at least 15 sec yielded the largest}{\fs20  amount of recall performance error, compared to the other time and activity conditions.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Several attempts have been made to explain why proactive interference affects remembering movement information. One plausible suggestion is that when the proactive interference takes the form of other movements, especially those that are similar to the criterion activity, }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 confusion}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  occurs. The individual is unable to make the criterion movement precisely because of the influence of the prior activities on the distinctiveness of the criterion movement.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Proactive interference seems to occur primarily \line when there is similarity between what is to be remembered and the interfering activity. This similarity seems to relate to \ldblquote attribute\rdblquote  similarity. That is, if the information to be remembered and the interfering activity relate to the same movement \u173 ?
attribute or characteristic, then proactive interference will build up as the number of similar movements preceding the movements to be remembered increases. For example, several studies by Ste-Marie and \line her colleagues in Canada have shown that gymnastics judges demonstrate proactive interference effects by exhibiting a judging bias during \u173 ?
actual competition based on what they observed a gymnast }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 does}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  during warm-up sessions (Ste-Marie & Lee, 1991; Ste-Marie & Valiquette, 1996; Ste-Marie, Valiquette, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 & Taylor, 2001).\par }\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Proactive interference in long-term memory.\u8194\'20}
{\fs20 For movement information in long-term memory, the role of proactive interfering activities is not well known although the concept of negative transfer }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 of learning, which will be discussed in chapter 13, \line }{\fs20 is relevant to our understanding of proactive interference in long-term memory (see Koedijker, Oudejans, & Beek, 2010). An important feature of proactive interference in long-term memory is that we can quite readily overcome its effects by actively rehearsing the information. For motor skills, rehearsal occurs as we practice. This means that when we \u173 ?
actively practice a skill, we strengthen its representation in memory and thus notice few, if any, effects of proactive interference (see Panzer & Shea, 2008; Panzer, Wilde, & Shea, 2006).}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Retroactive Interference\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 If an interfering activity occurs after we perform a movement we need to remember (i.e., }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4
during}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  the retention interval) and results in poorer retention performance than if no activity had occurred, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 the forgetting is said to be due to }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw1 retroactive }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4\u173 ?
interference}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 .}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb120\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-4\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Retroactive interference in working memory.}
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-4\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
In working memory, it seems that rather than just any activity causing interference to the extent that \u173 ?retention performance is negatively affected, the }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 degree of similarity}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  between the interfering activity and the movement that must be remembered is an important factor. For example, participants in \u173 ?
experiments by Smyth and Pendleton (1990) were shown a sequence of four movements, such as a \u173 ?forward bend of the head, both arms raised to shoulder level in front of the body, a bend of the knees, and left leg raised to the side. Following a \u173 ?
retention interval, they had to perform these movements, either in sequence (serial recall) or in any order (free \u173 ?recall).\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The influence of five different retention interval time and activity conditions on recall performance can be seen in figure 10.3}
{\fs20 . As you can see, these results showed that only when the retention interval involved subjects in recalling movements that were similar to those they had to remember did recall performance significantly suffer from activity in the retention interval.\par }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 Another characteristic of retroactive interfer}{\fs20 ence effects in working memory is one that we discussed for proactive interference. That is, activity }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 during the retention interval causes interference }{\fs20 that }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i increases recall performance error only when there is a certain amount of activity}
{\fs20 . As long as the amount of information stays within this limit, remembering is not affected. However, when that limit is exceeded, forgetting occurs, which results in recall performance error increase.}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Thus, the available research evidence indicates that retroactive interference for remembering just-presented movements occurs in two specific circumstances. These are situations when the activity during the retention interval is similar to the movements that must be remembered and when this activity and the movements to be remembered exceed working memory or attention-capacity limits.\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Retroactive interference and long-term memory.}
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 \u8194\'20\line }{\fs20 It appears that retention interval length and/or activity does not have the same forgetting effects for all types of motor skills stored in }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i long-term memory.}{\fs20  Research evidence indicates that }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i certain types of motor skills are remembered better over long \u173 ?
periods than are other types.}{\fs20  Your own experiences may provide some support for this. You probably had very little trouble remembering how to ride a bicycle, even after not having been on one for several years. However, you probably did experience some difficulty in putting together the pieces of a puzzle that you had assembled quickly around the same time you learned to ride a bicycle.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 The characteristic of skills that distinguishes these }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 two situations relates to one of the classification }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 systems discussed in chapter 1. That is, }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i con\u173 ?tinuous motor skills}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
 are typically more resistant to long-term forgetting than are discrete skills, especially when the skill involves producing a series of discrete movements in what we referred to as a serial motor skill.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Several reasons have been suggested to explain why this retention difference occurs. One is the difference in the }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 size of the verbal component}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  of the two types of skills. Serial discrete skills have a large verbal component, whereas this is small for continuous skills. This characteristic is significant because the verbal component of skills seems to deteriorate over time more readily than motor com}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ponents. Another reason is that continuous skills are }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
practiced more}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  than are discrete skills. This is evident if you consider what a \ldblquote trial\rdblquote  is for these two types of skills. One trial for a discrete skill is usually one performance of the skill, whereas one trial for a continuous skill is several repetitions of the skill over a much longer period of time. Thus, fifty trials of a continuous skill yield many more practice repetitions of the skill than do fifty trials of a discrete skill.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Movement Characteristics Related to Memory Performance\par }\pard\plain \s18\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang2057
{\fs20 Location and Distance Characteristics}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Actions have many characteristics that we can store in memory. For example, we could store the spatial position}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  or location}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  of various points of a movement, such as the beginning and the end point of a golf swing. We could also store the distance of a movement, its velocity, its force, and/or the direction of a movement. Two of these, }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 location}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  and }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 distance,}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
 have been \u173 ?extensively examined with regard to how easily they can be stored in and retrieved from memory.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Investigation of the issue was very popular in the 1970s and focused primarily on the short-term storage in working memory of spatial positioning movements of the arm. The initial research studies found that movement end-point location is remembered better than movement distance (e.g., Diewert, 1975; Hagman, 1978; Laabs, 1973). In other words, they were better at reproducing the final position of the arm than how far the arm had moved. }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 This can be tested by varying the start position of a movement but keeping the end location constant versus varying the start position and the end location but keeping the distance constant.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  An important finding showed that when movement end-point location \u173 ?information is a relatively reliable recall cue, people will use a \u173 ?
location-type strategy to recall the movement (Diewert & Roy}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  1978). However, when location information is totally unreliable and only distance \u173 ?
information will aid recall, people will use some nonkinesthetic strategy, such as counting, to help \u173 ?remember the distance of the criterion movement.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Another characteristic of remembering location information is that an arm}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
movement end location is more easily }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 remembered}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  when it is within the person\rquote s own body space (e.g., Chieffi, Allport, &}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Woodfin, 1999; Larish & Stelmach}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 1982). For limb-}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 positioning movements, people typically associate the end location of a movement with a body part and use that as a cue to aid their recall performance. Other research, which will be considered later, suggests that people will also spontaneously associate the end location of limb positions with well-known objects, such as a clock face, to aid recall.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 What does all this mean for teaching motor skills? One implication is that if limb positions are important for successful performance of the skill, the instructor can emphasize these positions in ways that will facilitate learning the skill. For example, if you are teaching a beginner a golf swing, the important phases of the swing that he or she should \u173 ?
concentrate on are critical location points in the swing. The keys could be the beginning point of the\u8239 ?backswing or the location point of the top of the backswing. Or if a therapist or athletic trainer is working with a patient who needs to work on \u173 ?
flexing or extending his or her knee, emphasizing the position of the lower leg can help the patient \u173 ?remember where the last movement was or to \u173 ?
establish a goal for \u173 ?future flexion attempts. If a dancer or Pilates student is having difficulty remembering where her arm should be during a particular movement sequence, a body-part cue about the location of the arm can help her remember the position more effectively.\par }
{\fs20 A note of caution is important here. Instructors of motor skills should not direct people to visually look to the location where the limb should move. Research has consistently shown that visually remembered locations for limb movements will be different from those remembered kinesthetically (see Simmering, Peterson, Darling, & Spencer, 2008, for a review of this research). This means that rather than enhancing the remembering of limb movement positions, the addition of visual information negatively influences how the positions are remembered.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Meaningfulness of the Movement\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Another characteristic that influences remembering movements is the }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1
meaningfulness}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  of the movement. A movement or sequence of movements can be considered meaningful to an individual if that person can readily relate the movement to something he or she knows. For example, a movement that forms the shape of a triangle is considered more meaningful than one that makes an unfamiliar, abstract pattern. Or, if a movement is similar to one the person can do, then the new movement being learned takes on increased meaningfulness to the person.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The results of an experiment by Laugier and }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Cadopi (1996) illustrate the influence movement }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 meaningfulness has on remembering movements. Adult novice dancers watched a video of a skilled dancer perform a four-element sequence of dance }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 movements, each of which involved two to four head, body, and/or limb movements. One sequence, which the researchers labeled as a \ldblquote concrete\rdblquote  sequence, was a sequence commonly performed in dance. Another sequence, labeled as an \ldblquote abstract\rdblquote  sequence, involved elements that did not belong to any particular style of dance. After fifteen viewings of the dancer perform-\line ing the \u173 ?
sequences, the participants performed the \u173 ?sequence one time. Analysis of the participants\rquote  \u173 ?perfor\u173 ?\u173 ?\u173 ?\u173 ?\u173 ?\u173 ?
mance indicated that the observation of the\u8239 ?concrete sequence led to better form and quality than the observation of the abstract sequence (see \line }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 figure 10.4). Interviews of the participants \u173 ?indicated that the concrete sequence had a higher \u173 ?
degree of meaningfulness to them, which helped them remember the sequence when they performed it.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }
\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Strategies That Enhance Memory Performance\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 There are several different strategies people can use to help them remember important movement char}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
acteristics of a skill, which in turn facilitate learning}{\fs20  the skill. Note that some of these strategies take advantage of the movement characteristics we }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 just discussed that are more easily remembered }{\fs20 than others. We will consider three general strategies that research evidence has shown to influence how well a movement is remembered.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Increasing a Movement\rquote s Meaningfulness\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 When people first practice a new skill, it is very likely that the skill will require that they coordinate their body and limbs in a new way. This characteristic makes it also likely that the new coordination pattern of movements will be more abstract than it \u173 ?
is concrete. That is, the skill typically has little \u173 ?inherent \ldblquote meaningfulness}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \rdblquote  to the learner in terms \u173 ?
of\u8239 ?spatial and temporal characteristics of the limb coordination needed to perform the skill. As you saw earlier in this discussion, movements that are higher in their\u8239 ?
meaningfulness will be remembered better than those low in meaningfulness. The instructor can take advantage of this characteristic by presenting to the learner a strategy that will \u173 ?
increase the meaningfulness of the movements required \u173 ?to\u8239 ?perform the skill. Two strategies are \u173 ?especially \u173 ?
effective: visual imagery and verbal \u173 ?labels.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The use of }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 visual metaphoric imagery}{\fs20  as a memory strategy involves developing in your mind a picture of what a movement is like. As an instructor, it is best to use a metaphor for an image of something that is very familiar to the learner. For example, rather than provide the complex instructions for how to coordinate the arm movements to perform a sidestroke in swimming, the instructor can provide the learners with a useful metaphoric image to use while practicing the stroke. One such image is of themselves picking an apple from a tree with one hand, bringing the apple down, and putting the apple in a basket. }
{\fs20 In a rehabilitation context, physical therapists often teach the squat movement by having the patient visualize themselves sitting down on a toilet seat rather than describing each of the joint motions involved in the movement.}
{\fs20  Also, research by Nordin and Cumming (2005, 2007) has shown the beneficial use of metaphoric imagery by dancers to help them perform and remember how to perform complex dance skills. (The use of imagery as an instructional strategy will be discussed in more detail in chapter 19.)\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Another effective strategy that increases the meaningfulness of a movement is to attach a meaningful }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3
verbal label}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  to the movement. One of the earliest demonstrations of the beneficial influence of attaching verbal labels to movements was by John Shea (1977), who had participants move a lever to a stop on a semicircular arm-positioning apparatus. When they arrived at the criterion location, those in one group were provided with a number that corresponded to the clockface location of the criterion \u173 ?
location; another group received an irrelevant verbal label such as a nonsensical three-letter syllable; \u173 ?another group received no verbal label about the \u173 ?
criterion location. Results, as seen in figure 10.5}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 , indicated that the group given a clockface label showed no increase in error over a 60 sec unfilled retention interval, whereas the other two groups showed a large increase in recall error. In a related experiment, Winther and Thomas (1981) showed that when useful verbal labels are attached to positioning movements, retention performance of young children (age seven) can become equivalent to that of adults.\par }
{\fs20 There are at least four reasons why the use of \u173 ?visual metaphoric imagery and verbal labels aid the learning of complex motor skills. First, they reduce the complexity of the verbal instructions that would be needed to describe all the movements involved in performing the skill and their relationships to each other. }
{\fs20 This, in turn, reduces the demands on working memory.}{\fs20  }{\fs20 Second, they help change an abstract, complex array of movements to a more concrete, meaningful set of movements}
{\fs20  that is easier to remember}{\fs20 . Third, they direct the performer\rquote s attention focus to the outcome of the movements rather than to the movements themselves, which, as we discussed in chapter 9, enhances the performance of skills. And fourth, they speed up the movement planning process by facilitating the retrieval of the appropriate memory representation of the action (Johnson, 1998).}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Intention to Remember\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In all the memory experiments considered so far, participants have always known in advance that the movements they were presented or had to practice would be later subject to a recall test. But suppose they were not given this information in advance? Suppose they were told that the goal of the experiment was to see how well they could move their arms to a specified location. If an unexpected recall test was given later, how well would they recall the movements made earlier?\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-3\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Intentional and incidental memory.}
{\*\cs58\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-3\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
The two situations just described are known in the memory research literature as }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 intentional}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  and }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 incidental}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  memory situations, respectively. In addition to investigating the influence of intention to remember as an effective remembering strategy, the comparison of these two situations provides insight into the encoding of movement information processes. That is, do we store only information to which we give conscious attention, as in the case of the intentional memory situation, or do we store more information, as would be shown by good memory performance, in the incidental memory situation?}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 This question has received little research interest in the study of memory for movements. However, the research that has been done indicates that, in general, intention to remember leads to better remember\u173 ?
ing than no intention to remember. (See Crocker & }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Dickinson, 1984}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  for a review of this research; and }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Badets & Blandin, 2012 and }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
Badets, Blandin, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Bouquet, & Shea, 2006, for more recent example}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
s}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 .) Yet \u173 ?retention test performance in the incidental situation is typically better than if no previous experience with\u8239 ?
the test movements had occurred. In fact, some \u173 ?reports show incidental memory test performance to be as good as it was for the intentional situation.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 The investigation of intentional and incidental }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 memory strategies is an important one to increase \u173 ?
our\u8239 ?understanding of memory processes related to encoding and storing information. Research indicates that we encode and store much more information than \u173 ?
we}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3\u8239 ?are consciously aware of (see, for example, Perruchet, Chambaron, & Fervel-Chapus, 2003).\par }
{\fs20 One implication that the intentional and incidental memory research provides for instructional \u173 ?situations is that memory performance and skill learning can be enhanced by telling students when they begin to practice a skill that they will be tested on the skill later. The effect of this advance knowledge about a test is that students will undoubtedly increase the amount of effort given in practice, a characteristic that you will repeatedly see in this text as beneficial for memory and learning. Also, when there are specific characteristics of a skill }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 performance situation that must be remembered }{\fs20 for a later test, a better test performance will result from telling people what these characteristics are.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb241\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Subjective Organization\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 A strategy frequently used by learners for large amounts of information is grouping or organizing the information into units. This strategy, which is known as }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 subjective organization,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  involves the organizing of information that must be remembered in a way that is meaningful to the individual. Other terms that researchers have used to describe this strategy are }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i chunking, clustering,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  and }{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i grouping,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  among others. An example of implementing this strategy is commonly seen when people need to learn a long monologue for a play, or a list of terms for a test. They often will organize the monologue or list by dividing it into shorter, more manageable chunks to begin memorizing the information. You would likely use a similar strategy if you had to play from memory a long piece of music on an \u173 ?
instrument, or had to learn a dance or gymnastics routine. In each of these situations, continued \u173 ?practice typically leads to increasing the size of the chunks.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Although the role of subjective organization in motor skill learning has not been the subject of a large amount of research, there is evidence indicating that when given the opportunity to subjectively organize a sequence of movements, some people }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 will spontaneously create an organized structure. And this subjectively determined organizational }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
structure imposed on the sequence benefits recall }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 performance (e.g., Magill & Lee, 1987). In addition, it is interesting to note that memory performance deficits often seen following a stroke (i.e., cerebro\u8209 ?
\line vascular accident) have been found to be due in }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 part to a lack of ability to implement effective organizational strategies (e.g., Lange, Waked, Kirshblum, &}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  DeLuca, 2000). Similarly, people with Parkinson\rquote s disease have been shown to have problems with }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3\u173 ?implementing a subjective organization strategy }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 without external guidance (Berger et al., 1999).\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Novices\rquote  and experts\rquote  use of subjective organization.\u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 One way to apply the benefit of subjective organization to motor skill learning situations is to }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 compare how novices and experts approach }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 the learning of a complex skill. }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 The novice}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  tends to consider complex motor skills as comprising many parts. As the beginner develops his or her ability to execute the skill, the number of components of the skill seems to decrease. This does not mean the structure of the skill itself has changed. Rather, the learner}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \rquote s view of the skill has changed. A good example is a dance or gymnastic floor exercise routine, where each of the routines is made up of many individual parts. To the beginner, a dance routine is thought of step by step and movement by movement. Beginning gymnasts think of a floor exercise as so many individual stunts. As they practice, their approach to the skills changes. They begin to organize the routines into units or groups of movements. Three or four component parts are now considered as one. The result will be performing the entire routine with the \u173 ?
requisite timing, rhythm, and coordination. With that result, moreover, will be the added effect of \u173 ?developing a more efficient means of storing the complex routine in memory.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Skilled performers organize information to such an extent that it appears they have an increased working memory capacity; this led Ericsson and Kintsch (1995) to propose the long-term working memory described earlier in this discussion. A good example of this type of subjective organization can be seen in the experiment with \ldblquote novice\rdblquote  and \ldblquote expert\rdblquote  eleven-year-old dancers by Starkes et al. (1987)}
{\fs20 , which}{\fs20  was mentioned earlier in the discussion of working memory capacity. When these dancers were presented \u173 ?
sequences of eight elements that were organized as in a ballet routine, the expert dancers recalled the routine almost perfectly, whereas the novices recalled about half of the sequence correctly. However, when the same number of elements was presented in an unstructured sequence, there was no difference between the skilled and novice dancers in terms of the number of elements they correctly recalled. This result indicates that the organizational structure of the sequence of dance movements was an important \u173 ?
factor in the experts}{\fs20 \rquote  recall perfor\u8209 ?\line mance. In an interesting anecdote, the researchers reported observing an adult principal national-level }
{\fs20 \line }{\fs20 ballet dancer being able to perform a sequence of ninety-six steps after having seen the sequence demonstrated one time. Thus, organization was apparently a strategy used to reduce the working memory load of this sequence and to increase the memorability of the sequence.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Similar organization effects were reported by Millslagle (2002) for experienced basketball players. Both male and female players were shown slides of structured and unstructured plays that could occur in game situations. On a recognition test given after the players viewed the slides, they more accurately \u173 ?
remembered having seen slides that included the structured plays. Interestingly, when results were compared for the players who were guards, forwards, and centers, the guards\rquote  recognition accuracy was higher than it was for the forwards and centers. Because guards have more experience determining and implementing plays than the other two positions, the results of this experiment further emphasize the \u173 ?
influence of expertise on the organizational structure of the information we store in memory.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Practice-Test Context Effects\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 An important influence on the retention of motor skills is the relationship between the context of practice and the context at the time of the test. The context of a movement relates to both the environmental conditions in which the movement is performed and characteristics related to the person performing the movement. For example, if a memory experiment is performed in a laboratory, the \u173 ?
environmental context includes such things as the room in which the experiment is done, the experimenter, the time of day, the noise the participant can hear, the lighting, and so on. Personal context involves such things as the mood of the individual, the limb used to make the movement, the sitting or standing position of the subject, and the sensory feedback sources that are available to the subject. As you will see in this section, differences in these conditions during the time the movement to be \u173 ?
remembered or learned is presented or practiced and during the time the movement must be recalled can influence the success of the recall performance.\par }
\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb380\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Encoding Specificity Principle}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 An important point to consider regarding the influence of movement context on remembering or learning a motor skill is the relationship between the practice and test contexts. In some situations, especially for closed skills, the test goal is essentially the same as the practice goal. That is, to shoot a free throw, you must stand in essentially the same place and shoot the ball through a hoop that is the same distance from you as it was when you practiced it. In such closed-skill situations, the }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\u173 ?}{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 encoding }{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1\u173 ?}{\*\cs56\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
specificity principle}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  \u173 ?applies.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The encoding specificity principle was introduced by Tulving and Thomson (1973). According to this principle, the more the test context resembles the practice context, the better the retention performance will be. Evidence that this principle applies to motor skills has come primarily from laboratory-based experiments (e.g., Lee & Hirota, 1980; Magill & Lee, 1987). However, as you will see in more detail in chapter 13 in the discussion of the concept of the transfer of learning, ample evidence exists to have confidence in generalizing this principle to the learning and performance of motor skills.\par }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 The encoding specificity principle is based }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 on \u173 ?research findings that indicate that }
{\*\cs53\fs20\b0\i the memory \u173 ?representation for an action has stored with it \u173 ?important sensory and motor feedback information that is specific to the context conditions in which the \u173 ?
action was practiced.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  Thus, the more the test conditions match the practice conditions, the more accurate the test performance will be expected to be.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\fs20 The practical implications of the encoding specificity principle seem especially relevant to learning closed skills. In a closed skill, the test context is typically stable and predictable. Because of this, practice conditions can be established that will closely mimic the test conditions. In these cases, then, the more similar the practice setting is to the test setting, the higher the probability o}
{\fs20 f}{\fs20  successful performance during the test. Consider, for example, practice for shooting free throws in a basketball game. Free throws are always one, two, or one-and-one situations. According to the encoding specificity principle, it is essential that \u173 ?
players have practice experiences in which these gamelike \u173 ?conditions prevail. This does not say that this is the only way that free throws can be practiced. However, if game performance is the test of interest, it is essential that gamelike practice be provided.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Consider also a physical therapy example where a knee joint replacement patient is working on knee joint flexion and extension. Based on the encoding specificity principle, because test conditions involve active limb movement, practice conditions should emphasize active rather than passive limb movement. Similar practice-test relationships can be established for a variety of skill practice situations.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f5\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li120\ri0\sb0\sa260\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs18 Summary}{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s20\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 Memory is best viewed as consisting of two }{\fs20 functional component systems: working memory and long-term memory, with each having three \u173 ?
subsystems.\par }\pard\plain \s20\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
